WEBVTT

00:01.034 --> 00:02.835
<i>You're watching</i>
The Last Man On Earth.

00:02.837 --> 00:06.138
We were known as KWA,
Knitters with Attitude.

00:06.140 --> 00:09.308
<i>Catch all-new episodes Sunday.</i>
<i>And check out</i>
<i>our other Fox programs--</i>

00:09.310 --> 00:12.478
Brooklyn Nine-Nine,
The Grinder<i> and</i> Grandfathered.

00:12.480 --> 00:14.513
I'm a grand--
I'm a grandfather?

00:14.515 --> 00:15.748
<i>Only on Fox.</i>

00:18.685 --> 00:20.285
<i>Previously on</i>
The Last Man on Earth...
Did you ask the group

00:20.287 --> 00:21.286
<i>if they wanted some bacon?</i>

00:21.288 --> 00:22.554
Crickets are alive!

00:22.556 --> 00:24.823
TANDY:
<i>They're all eatin' bugs, man.</i>

00:24.825 --> 00:28.961
Why did I have to dress
the dummy in Gordon's clothes?

00:28.963 --> 00:30.629
(sobbing)

00:30.631 --> 00:32.464
I'm sick and tired of
you hitting on Carol!

00:32.466 --> 00:33.799
TANDY:
<i>All the evidence is gone.</i>

00:33.801 --> 00:35.334
Todd, do you have anything
you want to tell us?

00:35.336 --> 00:37.403
The fat guy ate
the bacon! (sobbing)

00:37.405 --> 00:38.670
(whispers):
Thanks, man.

00:38.672 --> 00:39.671
Fist bump?

00:39.673 --> 00:41.273
Bump.

00:46.379 --> 00:48.514
(blow-dryer stops)

00:48.516 --> 00:50.115
(clicking)

00:59.392 --> 01:02.661
(to "The Heat Is On"):
♪ The heat is off ♪

01:02.663 --> 01:05.364
♪ Of this waffle maker ♪

01:05.366 --> 01:07.566
♪ Friggin' plug is in ♪

01:07.568 --> 01:09.334
♪ But the heat is off ♪

01:09.336 --> 01:10.936
♪ Ooh, ooh ♪

01:10.938 --> 01:13.705
♪ Better check that
wakka wakka wakka wakka ♪

01:13.707 --> 01:15.040
♪ Generator ♪

01:15.042 --> 01:17.609
♪ Friggin' gas gauge broke ♪

01:17.611 --> 01:19.912
♪ The gas gauge bro-oke ♪

01:19.914 --> 01:21.914
♪ It says half full ♪

01:21.916 --> 01:24.249
♪ But the sucker's on empty ♪

01:24.251 --> 01:27.052
♪ Gonna pour this ga-a-a-a-as ♪

01:27.054 --> 01:28.787
♪ In... ♪
What?

01:28.789 --> 01:30.589
♪ Gas looks weird ♪

01:30.591 --> 01:33.425
♪ It's friggin' super clumpy ♪

01:33.427 --> 01:36.095
♪ Like a ghost took a dump ♪

01:36.097 --> 01:38.197
♪ Into this gas can ♪

01:38.199 --> 01:40.265
(motor fails)
♪ Ooh, ooh... ♪

01:41.434 --> 01:44.269
♪ I'll eat you raw ♪

01:44.271 --> 01:46.638
♪ I'll eat you ra-haw ♪

01:46.640 --> 01:49.074
♪ Who needs heat? ♪

01:49.076 --> 01:51.243
♪ I'll eat a liquid waffle ♪

01:51.245 --> 01:52.878
♪ Ooh, hoo ♪

01:52.880 --> 01:55.280
♪ This waffle,
wakka wakka wakka wakka ♪

01:55.282 --> 01:57.516
(slurping)

02:00.653 --> 02:02.721
♪ Sucks. ♪

02:04.057 --> 02:06.225
(hammering nearby)

02:06.227 --> 02:08.660
Phil! Will you hold it down
out there?

02:08.662 --> 02:10.662
I'm trying to concentrate.

02:10.664 --> 02:12.498
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm gonna try

02:12.500 --> 02:14.399
and fix your stuff
more quietly now.

02:14.401 --> 02:15.601
(laughs): Nice!

02:15.603 --> 02:17.469
Lifting the bricks
is the hardest part.

02:17.471 --> 02:19.071
MELISSA:
Yeah, I imagine your fingers

02:19.073 --> 02:20.472
must still be pretty slippery

02:20.474 --> 02:22.141
from all the friggin'
bacon grease.

02:22.143 --> 02:24.510
Aw, come on, Melissa,
how many times do I have to say

02:24.512 --> 02:25.911
I'm sorry?
TANDY: Wait,
you're sorry?

02:25.913 --> 02:27.513
That's funny,
I thought your name was Todd.

02:27.515 --> 02:28.680
Boom, still got it.

02:28.682 --> 02:31.083
(chuckles) So, uh, what's
going on out here, huh?

02:31.085 --> 02:33.652
Playing a little gold bar Jenga?
Little GBJ?

02:33.654 --> 02:35.521
You want to join us?
Well, I'd love to,

02:35.523 --> 02:37.789
but I got a little gas situation
on my hands. Hey, Phil,

02:37.791 --> 02:39.925
could you check
this out for me?

02:39.927 --> 02:41.460
You have knowledge
of this kind of bull-crap.

02:41.462 --> 02:42.628
Look at this.

02:42.630 --> 02:43.795
OTHERS:
Ew.

02:43.797 --> 02:45.931
Yep, it's gone bad.

02:45.933 --> 02:47.666
Gas goes bad?

02:47.668 --> 02:49.868
(chuckles):
I told you this a million times.

02:49.870 --> 02:51.436
Nobody remembers this?

02:51.438 --> 02:53.305
No, I remember, but, you know,
just for those

02:53.307 --> 02:54.773
who might not
have been paying attention

02:54.775 --> 02:55.941
at the time-- shame on you--

02:55.943 --> 02:57.676
you know, maybe run
over it one more time,

02:57.678 --> 02:59.344
just the ABCs of it?

02:59.346 --> 03:00.679
Unbelievable.

03:00.681 --> 03:03.015
Gas lasts about three years.

03:03.017 --> 03:04.349
Three years.
Yep, I remember that.

03:04.351 --> 03:06.185
Diesel lasts a year or two
longer than gas.

03:06.187 --> 03:07.719
One or two... more. yeah.

03:07.721 --> 03:09.555
And then there's jet fuel...
Fuels jets.

03:09.557 --> 03:10.856
...which lasts longer
than diesel

03:10.858 --> 03:12.658
but still has
an expiration date.

03:12.660 --> 03:14.126
Date when it expires.

03:14.128 --> 03:16.895
None of these are
long-term solutions.

03:16.897 --> 03:18.497
Nobody remembers this?

03:18.499 --> 03:20.699
Well, you know what?

03:20.701 --> 03:22.367
I'm glad this is happening.

03:22.369 --> 03:24.002
Because now you finally realize

03:24.004 --> 03:26.538
that Malibu is
the worst place we could be.

03:26.540 --> 03:29.074
Shut your ever-loving tongue!
(others speaking angrily)

03:29.076 --> 03:30.509
Phil, you are such a crank!

03:30.511 --> 03:32.044
Why can't you appreciate
where you are

03:32.046 --> 03:34.346
for once?
You know what I appreciate?

03:34.348 --> 03:36.381
Food. And fresh water.

03:36.383 --> 03:38.383
And there's very
little of that here.
And now that the gas

03:38.385 --> 03:41.753
has gone bad, it's gonna be very
tough to find fresh supplies.

03:41.755 --> 03:43.755
All right,
so what do you suggest, Phil?

03:43.757 --> 03:46.892
We need to go
to a more livable place, guys.

03:46.894 --> 03:49.561
We are not moving.
We love Malibu.

03:49.563 --> 03:52.364
Look, guys, there comes a point
where we need to decide

03:52.366 --> 03:54.166
whether we continue
to live for today,

03:54.168 --> 03:55.934
or actually plan for tomorrow.

03:55.936 --> 03:57.502
You know, Phil might be right.

03:57.504 --> 04:00.772
Malibu's good for now, but what
about when we start having kids?

04:00.774 --> 04:03.175
Well, let's just
not have kids, then.

04:04.410 --> 04:06.178
ERICA:
Yeah, I'm good with that.

04:06.180 --> 04:08.580
Okay, so it's decided--
no kids,

04:08.582 --> 04:10.515
we're gonna live for the now,

04:10.517 --> 04:12.351
and the now
starts now.

04:12.353 --> 04:14.720
(chanting quietly):
YOLO. YOLO.

04:14.722 --> 04:16.622
(growing louder):
YOLO. YOLO.

04:16.624 --> 04:18.390
YOLO! YOLO!

04:18.392 --> 04:21.793
YOLO! YOLO! YOLO! YOLO! YOLO!

04:21.795 --> 04:23.595
(groans)

04:23.597 --> 04:26.765
You know, I'm-I'm really tired
of doing all the work out here.

04:26.767 --> 04:29.801
Maybe<i> I</i> should get
a breather, huh?

04:29.803 --> 04:32.604
Have myself a little YOLO time.

04:32.606 --> 04:34.606
That's what I'm gonna do.

04:34.608 --> 04:36.942
Yeah. Here's the tool belt.

04:36.944 --> 04:39.444
You'll be just fine
without me.

04:39.446 --> 04:41.713
ERICA:
Yep.
All right, good luck.

04:44.150 --> 04:47.352
I thought he was
gonna take his pants off.

04:49.289 --> 04:51.156
I am so thrown
for a loop.

04:51.158 --> 04:52.457
I thought
everyone wanted

04:52.459 --> 04:53.792
to have babies.

04:53.794 --> 04:55.794
Hey, don't worry, Care Bear.
They'll come around.

04:55.796 --> 04:56.962
I don't know.

04:56.964 --> 04:58.330
You heard Phil.

04:58.332 --> 05:02.134
Nobody wants to raise a baby
in the wastelands of Malibu.

05:02.136 --> 05:04.936
Maybe we<i> should</i> move.
Hey, what if

05:04.938 --> 05:07.139
I was to whip this place
into shape?

05:07.141 --> 05:08.607
How you gonna do that?

05:08.609 --> 05:10.142
Phil's not the only one
around here

05:10.144 --> 05:11.777
with skills to pay the bills.

05:11.779 --> 05:14.479
You gonna pay the bills
with your skill set?

05:14.481 --> 05:15.814
I'm gonna try.

05:15.816 --> 05:17.582
I think that's a
great idea, Phil.

05:17.584 --> 05:20.085
You know, it could gain
some points with the group.

05:20.087 --> 05:22.421
I'm not trying to gain points--
that sounds gross.

05:22.423 --> 05:25.123
I'm trying to<i> earn</i> points.
There's a big difference.

05:25.125 --> 05:26.591
Well,<i> I</i> can see
the difference.

05:26.593 --> 05:28.960
And I think soon the
others will, too.

05:28.962 --> 05:30.929
I mean, Todd
already has, huh?

05:30.931 --> 05:32.364
Yeah.

05:32.366 --> 05:36.068
It's so nice to see the two
of you fisting each other again.

05:37.337 --> 05:38.704
Oh. Yeah, yeah.

05:38.706 --> 05:40.038
You keep this up,

05:40.040 --> 05:42.908
pretty soon you'll be fisting
the whole community.

05:44.644 --> 05:46.678
Hope to.

05:48.681 --> 05:50.515
Hey, buddy.

05:50.517 --> 05:51.616
What's all this?

05:51.618 --> 05:53.352
Ah. Well, you know,

05:53.354 --> 05:55.887
since it seems like we're
committing to Malibu here,

05:55.889 --> 05:58.657
and Phil's out on strike,
thought I'd take it upon myself

05:58.659 --> 06:00.659
to give her
a little makeover.

06:00.661 --> 06:02.027
Solar panels, huh?

06:02.029 --> 06:04.529
Yeah, let's get a little power
in this tower, huh?

06:04.531 --> 06:05.831
(chuckles):
Yeah.

06:05.833 --> 06:07.632
Little wattage in this cottage.

06:07.634 --> 06:09.167
Little sizzle in the hizzle.

06:09.169 --> 06:12.003
(chuckles):
Love it.

06:12.005 --> 06:14.139
Ah. Well, you need a hand?

06:14.141 --> 06:15.907
No, got two already,
but I'd love some company.

06:15.909 --> 06:17.509
Well, then you got
some company.

06:17.511 --> 06:19.544
You're not just company, bud,
you're a whole corporation.

06:19.546 --> 06:21.313
That's not a weight crack,
by they way,

06:21.315 --> 06:23.382
that's speaking of the size
of your friendship.
Well,

06:23.384 --> 06:26.318
you're a corporation, too, and
I<i> am</i> talking about your weight.

06:26.320 --> 06:28.086
Ha! It's good to have you back.
I've missed this.

06:28.088 --> 06:29.488
I have, too.
Yeah.

06:29.490 --> 06:31.556
So, uh, you know how
to install these things?

06:31.558 --> 06:34.226
Well, you know, I watched Phil
put 'em up in Tucson,

06:34.228 --> 06:36.595
and I got the general gist--
you know, you just

06:36.597 --> 06:38.730
throw these suckers out
where the sun hits 'em,

06:38.732 --> 06:41.733
and that's gonna send
a little juice into
that wire and, uh,

06:41.735 --> 06:44.936
plug that into something,
and then, zap, electricity.

06:44.938 --> 06:46.705
Well, good, good.

06:46.707 --> 06:48.507
That's great.

06:48.509 --> 06:50.275
Something on your mind, bud?

06:50.277 --> 06:51.843
Yeah, I'm-I'm a little bummed

06:51.845 --> 06:53.245
about Melissa not wanting
to have babies.

06:53.247 --> 06:55.514
You know, I thought
we were on the same page there.

06:55.516 --> 06:57.015
I think
she's still a little upset

06:57.017 --> 06:59.351
about the whole bacon thing.
Then you know what?

06:59.353 --> 07:02.087
Why don't you jump in here?
A little community consciousness

07:02.089 --> 07:04.089
could just change
your fortunes, huh?

07:04.091 --> 07:05.524
Women love a doer.

07:05.526 --> 07:07.192
Thanks, man.
Hey, you see
something over there

07:07.194 --> 07:09.060
that looks like something
that wire would plug into?

07:09.062 --> 07:11.730
I don't. I think
just this...

07:11.732 --> 07:13.532
empty cardboard box.

07:13.534 --> 07:15.434
(chuckles): Yeah.
Well, I don't think<i> that's</i> it.

07:15.436 --> 07:16.535
(laughs):
No.

07:17.970 --> 07:19.971
Does it have, like,
a little plug-sized hole

07:19.973 --> 07:23.308
or anything?
No. I-I think it's just the
box that the panels came in.

07:23.310 --> 07:24.976
Yeah, that's
what I thought. Yeah.

07:24.978 --> 07:27.979
Oh, look, says here
you got to plug it
into a junction box.

07:27.981 --> 07:29.548
Oh, do we have a junction box?

07:29.550 --> 07:31.817
I don't know
what that is.
Huh.

07:31.819 --> 07:34.953
And we're sure
it's not that cardboard box?

07:35.988 --> 07:37.255
I-I don't think so.

07:37.257 --> 07:39.458
(chuckles):
Yeah. I don't, either.
(laughs)

07:39.460 --> 07:42.994
Well, maybe we should
pick one of those up, huh?

07:42.996 --> 07:44.629
Yeah. That's a pretty good call.
Yeah?

07:44.631 --> 07:46.331
Want to go get some food first?

07:46.333 --> 07:48.333
I could eat.
Okay, great.
Well, then food,

07:48.335 --> 07:50.769
junction box store,
then we light this mother up.

07:50.771 --> 07:52.103
Bam. Ha-ha!

07:52.105 --> 07:53.772
(slaps Todd's behind)
Whoa!

07:53.774 --> 07:55.607
Got me.
Got to stay on your toes.

07:55.609 --> 07:56.842
TODD:
I certainly do.

07:56.844 --> 07:58.310
(low crackling)

08:03.649 --> 08:05.750
Yeah, should be
a pretty open-and-shut case

08:05.752 --> 08:07.752
once we get down to beeswax.

08:07.754 --> 08:10.422
Couple of men stretching
their wings out under the sun.

08:10.424 --> 08:11.490
(chuckles):
Yeah.

08:11.492 --> 08:13.592
We're gonna have it done
by nap time.

08:13.594 --> 08:15.093
(electrical crackling)

08:15.095 --> 08:17.028
Uh, Tandy?

08:17.030 --> 08:19.598
I-I think we got a problem.

08:22.835 --> 08:24.603
Well, this is

08:24.605 --> 08:26.438
a shocking turn of events.

08:26.440 --> 08:28.373
Boom, I still got it.

08:28.375 --> 08:30.041
TODD:
That looks kind of dangerous.

08:30.043 --> 08:32.177
It's definitely
in the dangerous family.

08:32.179 --> 08:33.945
Let's give her a poke.

08:34.881 --> 08:37.616
Careful.

08:37.618 --> 08:39.484
Careful's my middle name, bro.

08:39.486 --> 08:41.186
Just kidding. It's Tandy.

08:41.188 --> 08:43.121
(electrical crackling)

08:43.123 --> 08:46.024
Yeah, that's all
in the family.

08:46.026 --> 08:47.459
TODD:
At least it's not stuck anymore.

08:47.461 --> 08:50.061
At least
it's not stuck anymore.
Yeah.

08:50.063 --> 08:51.530
Knock, knock.

08:52.798 --> 08:54.399
Hey, Carol.

08:54.401 --> 08:56.801
I've just been thinking
about what you said

08:56.803 --> 08:59.638
regarding not wanting a baby,
and I have to admit,

08:59.640 --> 09:01.306
I was a little thrown.

09:01.308 --> 09:03.241
I'm sorry.

09:03.243 --> 09:05.310
Well, not as sorry
as you're gonna be

09:05.312 --> 09:08.079
if you never meet
this little guy.

09:09.482 --> 09:12.317
Whoa. What-what is that?

09:12.319 --> 09:15.520
This... is everything

09:15.522 --> 09:18.723
of which you never knew
you ever dreamed.

09:18.725 --> 09:21.860
This is what you and Todd's
baby would look like.

09:21.862 --> 09:23.562
(high-pitched, gruff):
Mama.

09:23.564 --> 09:25.363
Kind of puts

09:25.365 --> 09:27.165
a little different spin
on things, doesn't it?

09:27.167 --> 09:28.333
Mm, yeah.

09:28.335 --> 09:29.701
That's a real game-changer.

09:29.703 --> 09:31.169
I knew you would think so.

09:31.171 --> 09:33.772
That's the spirit.
We can do it together.

09:33.774 --> 09:35.440
No, I'm not bringing
a baby into this world.

09:35.442 --> 09:36.942
There are no doctors.

09:36.944 --> 09:39.244
We're running out
of food, and...

09:39.246 --> 09:41.613
there are whale
carcasses everywhere.

09:41.615 --> 09:43.515
So you want my baby
to die alone?

09:43.517 --> 09:44.749
'Cause that's what's
gonna happen.

09:44.751 --> 09:46.885
We're all gonna die,
and he's gonna be

09:46.887 --> 09:49.721
75 and all alone because of you.

09:49.723 --> 09:52.190
It's a no.
No?

09:52.192 --> 09:55.627
Look that baby in the eyes
and tell it no.

09:55.629 --> 09:59.731
(high-pitched, gruff):
Mama, I want to exist.

09:59.733 --> 10:01.366
Carol, it's a no.

10:01.368 --> 10:03.034
Okay.

10:04.270 --> 10:05.470
Okay.

10:05.472 --> 10:07.806
(high-pitched, gruff):
Big mistake.

10:07.808 --> 10:10.709
(electrical crackling)

10:10.711 --> 10:12.777
All right, Todd,
it's safe.

10:12.779 --> 10:14.813
Now we just have to figure out

10:14.815 --> 10:17.082
a way to get her in
that junction box.

10:17.084 --> 10:18.316
Yeah, maybe we
should go get Phil.

10:18.318 --> 10:19.618
I bet he'd know
what to do.

10:19.620 --> 10:20.919
We can't get Phil. Okay?

10:20.921 --> 10:22.887
We have a chance here
to really prove ourselves

10:22.889 --> 10:25.423
to the community,
earn a little respect.

10:25.425 --> 10:27.993
I want to do this for them.

10:27.995 --> 10:29.728
Fine, okay.
What do we do?

10:29.730 --> 10:31.162
(sighs heavily)

10:31.164 --> 10:33.164
I don't know.

10:33.166 --> 10:36.735
Just got to figure out a way
to cut off her food supply.

10:37.937 --> 10:41.373
I think I have
just the idea.

10:42.341 --> 10:44.609
CAROL:
Hey, girl.

10:44.611 --> 10:45.977
(laughs):
Wow!

10:45.979 --> 10:47.579
Melissa!

10:47.581 --> 10:48.980
Am I right?

10:48.982 --> 10:50.582
What about Melissa?

10:50.584 --> 10:52.651
"What about Melissa?"

10:52.653 --> 10:55.353
Come on, she's being
as stubborn as a mule

10:55.355 --> 10:57.856
who refuses to reproduce.

10:57.858 --> 11:01.359
Yeah, I think I'm gonna have to
side with Melissa on this one.

11:01.361 --> 11:04.129
My sister had kids, and it
turned her nether regions

11:04.131 --> 11:06.498
into a real war zone.

11:06.500 --> 11:08.700
Her boobs were
like coin purses.

11:08.702 --> 11:10.969
Well, who doesn't love
a good coin purse?

11:10.971 --> 11:13.538
Put it in your hand
and feel all those coins?

11:13.540 --> 11:15.507
Just feel richer and richer

11:15.509 --> 11:17.542
the more you squeeze?
No.

11:17.544 --> 11:19.611
I'm not gonna
have kids, Carol.

11:20.613 --> 11:22.681
No.

11:22.683 --> 11:24.783
Chuck me another
duvet.
Here.

11:29.321 --> 11:30.955
Easy, buddy.

11:30.957 --> 11:33.191
She's dancing, man.

11:33.193 --> 11:35.326
Spitting fire.

11:35.328 --> 11:37.328
You working with me or
against me, you freaking tape?

11:37.330 --> 11:39.064
She is super pissed.

11:39.066 --> 11:41.299
Quick, Tan.
In and out, man.

11:41.301 --> 11:42.701
You got it.

11:42.703 --> 11:44.335
I'm out of tape!

11:44.337 --> 11:46.004
Oh, I'm not! Okay.

11:46.006 --> 11:47.806
Ah, the tape receded!

11:47.808 --> 11:50.241
Okay, you got it?
Got it.
I got it.

11:50.243 --> 11:51.643
Come on, that's it.

11:51.645 --> 11:52.644
